"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918425","Home Office","false","2018-06-11","<p>The Home Office collects recorded crime data for shoplifting from all police forces in England and Wales. These data are published at country, police force area (PFA), and community service partnership (CSP) level.</p><p>For the latest year to December 2017, police recorded crime for shoplifting in the most relevant areas were:</p><p>Wales: 20,352</p><p>Gwent PFA: 3,994</p><p>Torfaen CSP: 692</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-06-11T15:01:38.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918425/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918425/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-06","Shoplifting: Torfaen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will make an assessment of the level of shop theft in Torfaen compared with the constituency average in the last year.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","150716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918426","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-11","<p>Officials from the department have regular meetings and discussions with the communications team from the Cabinet Office's National Security Secretariat.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-06-11T16:36:09.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918426/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918426/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-06","National Security Communications Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 February 2018 to Question 126982, what meetings or discussions his Department has had with the National Security Communications Unit to date.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","150706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918427","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-12","<p>Officials are currently working with partners domestically and internationally to create a robust evidence base to inform the post-2020 biodiversity agenda and develop ambitious, impactful and integrated targets for terrestrial, coastal and marine environments.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-06-12T13:53:04.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918427/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918427/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-06","Seas and Oceans: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to page 119 of his Department's 25 Year Environment Plan, published on 11 January 2018, what evidence he considered to inform the UK’s position on a post-2020 target for ocean conservation under the Convention on Biological Diversity.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","150616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918428","Home Office","false","2018-06-11","<p>Our family reunion policy allows immediate pre-flight family members of those granted protection here to reunite with them. The Immigration Rules also provide for relatives with protection in the UK to sponsor children in serious and compelling circumstances and there is provision in the policy to grant visas outside the Rules in exceptional circumstances, which caters for family members who otherwise do not qualify under the Rules.</p><p>However, there is currently no provision in the Rules for children with refugee status in the UK to sponsor family members to join them. This is a considered policy position to avoid creating additional motives for children to be encouraged, or even forced, to leave their family, and risk dangerous journeys hoping to sponsor relatives later. We believe the best interests of children are reflected in remaining with their families, claiming asylum in the first safe country they reach – that is the fastest route to safety – and relying on resettlement schemes to travel safely.</p><p>We are listening carefully to calls to allow extended family members to qualify and are reviewing our approach to family reunion as part of the Government’s wider asylum and resettlement strategy. However, expanding the policy without careful thought could risk more people being put in harms’ way.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-11T14:00:56.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918428/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918428/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-06","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether he plans to make an assessment of the potential  (a) merits and (b) effect of allowing unaccompanied child refugees to sponsor a close relative to come to the UK.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","150707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918429","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-14","<p>There are approximately three to four full time equivalent permanent Defra staff, plus employees of Defra delivery bodies, working on preparations for the post-2020 framework under the Convention on Biological Diversity. Of these approximately two full time equivalent permanent staff are involved in negotiations.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-06-14T09:03:31.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918429/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918429/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-06","Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many full-time equivalent permanent staff of his Department are allocated to working on (a) preparations and (b) negotiations for the post-2020 framework under the Convention on Biological Diversity.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","150617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918430","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-13","<p>Food waste has a financial and environmental cost and is an issue requiring urgent action. Through our work with the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP), the UK has taken concerted action since 2007 and we are leading the way in the EU and internationally.</p><p> </p><p>The Courtauld Commitment 2025 is an ambitious ten-year voluntary agreement that brings together organisations across the food system to identify priorities, develop solutions and implement changes at scale, both within signatory organisations and by spreading new best practice across the UK. A core part of Courtauld 2025 is the measurement of food waste as this is vital to record progress towards meeting national and international targets.</p><p> </p><p>As part of Courtauld 2025 the Institute of Grocery Distribution and WRAP have worked with a wide range of business representatives to develop a set of principles on how to measure food that goes to waste. We support the actions of several retailers in measuring and publishing their food surplus and waste data and encourage other food businesses to follow their lead. The Resources and Waste Strategy will set out further policies on food waste later in the year.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-06-13T10:58:14.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918430/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918430/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-06","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department's resources and waste strategy due to be published later this year is planned to include policies to achieve greater transparency on the reporting by retailers of food waste produced (a) in their operations and (b) throughout their supply chains.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","150618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918431","Department for International Trade","false","2018-06-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Cardiff Central to the answer I gave her on 23 April 2018, UIN: 136499.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-06-11T16:46:59.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918431/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918431/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-06-06","Arms Trade: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, the gross value of licenced armed exports made to Israel (a) in total for and (b) in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","150708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918432","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-11","<p>Parliament previously agreed legislation that requires the 2018 Boundary Review to be based on the December 2015 electoral registers. Data published by ONS shows that the number of electors on these registers was 44,722,004. ONS has recently published data showing that there were 46,148,035 electors on the December 2017 electoral registers.</p><p>Registers used for a boundary review are necessarily a snapshot and the registers have always continued to change while a review takes place.</p><p>Without the current parliamentary boundary reviews, MPs could end up representing constituencies based on data that is over 20 years’ old, disregarding significant changes in demographics, house building and migration.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-06-11T15:21:22.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918432/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918432/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-06-06","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the difference is between the number of voters on the electoral register compared to the electoral register data used for the current parliamentary boundary review.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","150709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918433","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-11","<p>We recently undertook a call for evidence on a ban on the commercial third party sale of puppies and kittens in England. Evidence from the RSPCA in response to that exercise suggests between 40,000 and 80,000 puppies are sold by licensed pet shops each year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-11T15:46:59.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918433/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918433/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-06","Dogs: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the number of puppies sold by third party dealers in England in the last twelve months.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","150710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918434","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-11","<p>The UK has one of the strongest and most productive biotechnology sectors in the world. This Government is committed to ensuring a positive outcome for the sector, that enhances competitiveness and builds on the success that we are rightly proud of, as we exit the European Union. The EU (Withdrawal) Bill will ensure existing EU law continues to have effect in UK law after exit, providing businesses and stakeholders with maximum certainty as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-06-11T13:54:34.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918434/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/918434/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-06","Biotechnology: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans he has undertake a review of the regulatory and standards framework for the biotechnology industry after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","150555"
